Introducing the data set

The analyzed data consists of seven variables associated with peoples learning habits. Collected background information includes a persons gender and age. Learning habits were measured by verbal questions and measured with a scale from 0 to 5. The variables associated with learning are attitude as well as deep, strategic and surface learning skills. The learning outcome is measured as exam points. In total, learning processes of 166 persons were studied.

Figure 1 shows summary of the relationships and distributions of all studied variables. Of the studied persons majority are female (red) and around one third male (blue). In general the variables are nearly normally distributed, although some tails exist especially in data describing males. This may be due to the smaller group size, which allows the peripheral values to influence the distribution. The distribution in age is close to lognormal with most persons belonging to the age group 19-21.

Here the focus is on exam points as it is a concrete outcome of the learning strategies of the studied persons. From the last column in Figure 1 it can be seen that the difference between genders are generally low and, also due to the rather low group size, in this analysis no gender distinction will be made. The highest correlation with exam points occurs with attitude (r~0.44). Lower correlations occur with strategic learning skills (r~0.15) and surface learning skills (r~-0.14). These three variables will be studied further.

Figure 1. Summary of all variables in the study.

Modeling the data

Multiple linear regression model is fitted to the data in order to see whether exam points can be predicted by persons attitude, strategic and surface learning skills. The results are summarized in Table 1. The multiple R-squared of the fit is 0.21, indicating that 21 % of the variety in exam points can be attributed to these variables.

Of the three explanatory variables only attitude has P-value close to zero, indicating statistically significant correlation with exam points. According to the P-value, strategic and surface learning skills have no significant influence on success in exam. To confirm this, it is necessary to look at the standardized regression coefficients. They are 0.42, 0.11 and -0.05 for attitude, strategic and surface learning skills, respectively. It is seen that the standardized regression coefficients for attitude and strategic learning skills have the same order of magnitude. Therefore the strategic learning skills could potentially have importance for success in exam. However, as attitude is still clearly the most important predictor, both strategic and surface learning skills will be excluded from further analysis and I will only focus on attitude.

Table 1. Summary of results from fitting multiple linear regression model to exam points with attitude, strategic and surface learning skills as explanatory variables. (Residual standard error = 5.296, DF = 162, Multiple R-squared = 0.2074, Adjusted R-squared = 0.1927, F-statistic = 14.13, p-value = 3.156e-08)

In Table 2 the results of the linear regression fit with attitude as explanatory variable are summarized. Now the R-squared is 0.19, indicating that 19 % of the variety in exam points can be predicted with attitude. The adjusted R-squared is also 0.19, which is equal to the adjusted R-squared obtained with all three explanatory variables. Therefore it can be concluded that the strategic and surface learning skills do not increase, or increase only very slightly, the capability of the model to predict exam points.

Diagnostics of the linear fit

In order to estimate how well the fitted model represents the data and the assumption of normally distributed observations, distributions of the residuals are plotted and shown in Figure 2. Based on the Residuals vs Fitted plot, the spread of the residuals seems uniform and hence the assumed linear fit is considered reasonable for the analyzed data set. However, there appears to be three outliers (numbered 35, 56, 135, although not very well seen in the plot) with very large negative residuals. The theoretical quantiles (Normal Q-Q) show that the residuals are normally distributed except for the same three observations.

To determine whether these three outliers potentially influence the fitted linear regression model, residuals are plotted against leverage. Because all the points are within the Cooks distance, they are not influential in this case. Therefore the model can be concluded to be an appropriate representation of the data.

Figure 2. Diagnostics of the linear fit with attitude as explanatory variable.

Assignment 3: Logistic regression

In this analysis the aim is to study students alcohol use. The study group consists of two Portuguese secondary level schools. The data includes background information such as age, gender and address as well as different variables describing family life and freetime. Alcohol use is presented as daily consumption on both weekdays and weekends on the scale from 1 to 5. Alcohol use is defined as high if the average daily consumption is over 2. The school performance is measured as grades in Portuguese language and mathematics (scale from 0 to 20) and here the average of the two grades is used. Together the study includes 370 students for whom all information (32 variables) is available.

The figure above shows that the alcohol use in the study group is in general rather low. This is true especially for female students. This should be kept in mind when interpreting the results as the very few female students using lots of alcohol may influence the result considerably.

# draw a bar plot of each variable
gather(alc[-1]) %>% ggplot(aes(value)) + facet_wrap("key", scales = "free") + geom_bar()

In the figure above all variables are presented as bar plots. To study the causes and/or influences of high alcohol consumption (high_use), I chose to take a look at absences, final grades (G3), failures and family relations (famrel). Number of previous class failures are given from scale 1 to 4. Quality of family relations are measured from 1 to 5 (1 - very bad to 5 - excellent).

Initial hypothesis is that high alcohol use is related to frequent absences and lower grades. Previous class failures is assumed to have positive correlation with alcohol consumption. The quality of family relations is expected to be lower when alcohol consumption is high. It should be noted that to state whether these are causes or effects of high alcohol consumption is out of the scope of this analysis.

As seen in the figures below, the hypothesis of more frequent absences and lower grades with high alcohol consumption seems to be valid for male students. From the boxplot it is difficult to see whether or not the previous class failures are related to high alcohol use as the number of failures is so low in both groups. While the median value for family relations is rather good, 4, for both female and male students with or without high alcohol consumption, more students reported excellent (5) quality of family relations in the group with low alcohol consumption than in the group of high alcohol consumption indicating that the assumption is potentially valid. However, more thorough statistical analysis is needed to state the validity of these assumptions.

Logistic model is fitted to the data with high alcohol consumption as target variable and absences, final grades, class failures and family relations as explanatory variables. The low (< 0.05) p-value in absences and failures (shown in the summary below) indicates that they are statistically significant in predicting high alcohol consumption. Class failures and family relations do not show significant correspondence with the alcohol use.

# find logistic model with all four explanatory variables
m <- glm(high_use ~ absences + G3 + failures + famrel, data = alc, family = "binomial")

# print out a summary of the model
summary(m)

To further analyse the significance of the variables, the odds ratios and their confidence intervals are calculated (shown below). The confidence intervals for the odds ratios of grades and family relations include value 1. Therefore it can be concluded that there is no significant association between grades or family relations and high alcohol consumption. The confidence intervals for the odds ratios of absences and failures are above 1 and therefore both frequent absences and previous class failurescan be considered to increase the probability of high alcohol consumption. This supports the initial hypothesis.

Although grades and family relations are not found as significant predictors, the fact that their odds ratios are below 1 supports the hypothesis that grades and quality of family relations decrease with high alcohol consumption.

# compute odds ratios (OR)
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp

# compute confidence intervals (CI)
CI <- confint(m) %>% exp

Next it is tested how accurately the model with absences and failures as explanatory variables predicts high alcohol consumption. From the table and figure below, it is seen that in the observations around 70 % of the students reported low alcohol use while 30 % reported high alcohol use. For the prediction the same distribution is 92 % and 8 %. The model is therefore clearly missing an element predicting the risk of high alcohol consumption.

# predict() the probability of high_use
probabilities <- predict(m2, type = "response")

# add the predicted probabilities to 'alc'
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)

# use the probabilities to make a prediction of high_use
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

# tabulate the target variable versus the predictions
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$prediction) %>% prop.table() %>% addmargins()
##         prediction
## high_use      FALSE       TRUE        Sum
##    FALSE 0.66486486 0.03513514 0.70000000
##    TRUE  0.25135135 0.04864865 0.30000000
##    Sum   0.91621622 0.08378378 1.00000000
# initialize a plot of 'high_use' versus 'probability' in 'alc'
g <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = probability, y = high_use, col = prediction))

# define the geom as points and draw the plot
g + geom_point()

The number of wrong predictions in the training data is 0.29 meaning that in 29 % of the cases the students alcohol consumption was could not be correctly predicted with the given variables (absences and failures). However, as clearly over 50 % of the cases could be correctly predicted with the model, it seems more plausible to use the model in predicting the students alcohol use than simple guessing strategy.

# define a loss function (mean prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# compute the average number of wrong predictions in the training data
loss_func(class = alc$high_use, prob = alc$probability)
## [1] 0.2864865

Finally, I perform 10-fold cross-validation on the model. The results indicate that the test set performance is 0.30, which is larger than 0.26 obtained in the DataCamp model example. This means that the DataCamp model performance is better. In addition to absences and failures, the DataCamp model used gender as explanatory variable. As I noted in the beginning, the data shows very few female students with high alcohol consumption. Therefore, already based on the first figure, it should have been clear that being male increases the probability of high alcohol consumption. If I would refit the model, I would definitely include gender there as well.

# K-fold cross-validation
library(boot)
cv <- cv.glm(data = alc, cost = loss_func, glmfit = m, K = 10)

# average number of wrong predictions in the cross validation
cv$delta[1]
## [1] 0.3054054

Assignment 4: Clustering and classification

In this analysis I will use the Boston data set available at https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/MASS/html/Boston.html. The data contains information on 14 variables describing the housing values in 506 suburbs of Boston. Here I will focus on the per capita crime rate (crim) and study if there is correspondence to any other variable. To conduct this analysis, different methods to cluster and classify the observations are tested.

Distributions and correlations of different variables are shown below. The distribution of crime rates resembles logarithmic distribution with mostly very low crime rates. The distributions of other variables are also skewed. This may cause problems when linear discriminate analysis and clustering is applied as one of the assumptions behind the method is normally distributed observations.

ggpairs(Boston, lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))

The correlations are better seen from the correlation matrix (below). The crime rate has a slight positive correlation with accessibility to radial highways (rad) and property-tax rate (tax). It is interesting that the access to radial highways and property taxes are strongly correlated with each other. I cannot deduce a possible reason behind this correlations so I leave the explanations to the sociologists and economists.

Strong negative correlation is seen between weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres (dis) and proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940 (age). With growing distance the proportion of old houses decreases, which is likely due to the fact that the old houses are concentrated near the center. Newer houses were build further away from the center as the city expanded. Distance is negatively correlated also with concentration of nitrogen oxides (nox), which means the pollution level decreases with growing distance from the city centers. Also the proportion of non-retail business acres per town (indus) decreases further away from the centers. These are really not relevant for the analysis conducted here, so I will not go deeper into the other variables but concentrate on the crime rate.

Next the scaled crime rate is categorized using quantiles as the break points. From the distribution it was already seen that most of the areas in Boston had very low crime rates, making the use of quantiles in categorizing the data questionable. Labeling the categories with equal amount of observations as low, med_low, med_high and high is thus a bit misleading as most of the suburbs have very low crime rate.

# create a quantile vector of crim
bins <- quantile(boston_scaled$crim)

# create a categorical variable 'crime'
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, labels = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))

# look at the table of the new factor crime
table(crime)
## crime
##      low  med_low med_high     high 
##      127      126      126      127
# remove original crim from the dataset
boston_scaled <- dplyr::select(boston_scaled, -crim)

# add the new categorical value to scaled data
boston_scaled <- data.frame(boston_scaled, crime)

Despite the distribution, I go on fitting linear discriminant analysis on the data. Before that the data is divided into train and test sets. The train set consists of 80 % of the observations.

# number of rows in the Boston dataset 
n <- nrow(boston_scaled)

# choose randomly 80% of the rows
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)

# create train set
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]

# create test set 
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]

# save the correct classes from test data
correct_classes <- test$crim

# remove the crime variable from test data
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

For data classification, the linear discriminant analysis is fitted on the train set with categorical crime rate as the target variable and all the other variables as predictor variables. The fit is shown in the figure below. As can be seen from the figure, the four categories (low, med_low, med_high, high) form two clusters. Of these categories med_high (green) is divided between these two clusters. Therefore, it seems that two categories could be enough to represent the data: low and high crime rates.

# linear discriminant analysis
lda.fit <- lda(crime ~ ., data = train)

# print the lda.fit object
lda.fit

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

The linear discriminant analysis model fitted to the train dataset is used to predict the classes of the test data. The results are shown in the table below with comparison to the correct categories. It is seen that the majority of the results lie on the diagonal, meaning that the prediction matches the original categories rather well. There are no predictions that are completely off as the values in the bottom left and top right corners are zeros. Although the model seems to perform reasonably well, there are some discrepancies.

# predict classes with test data
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)

Because the linear discriminant analysis showed that perhaps only two categories are needed, Euklidean distance is calculated to represent similarities between observations and K-means clustering is applied to investigate the optimal number of categories. From the figure below it is seen that as the curve decreases strongly around value 2, two categories are sufficient to represent the similarities within the data.

# reload the Boston dataset
data("Boston")

# center and standardize variables
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)

# change the object to data frame
boston_scaled = as.data.frame(boston_scaled)

# euclidean distance matrix
dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled)

# look at the summary of the distances
summary(dist_eu)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.1343  3.4625  4.8241  4.9111  6.1863 14.3970
# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 3)

set.seed(123)

# determine the number of clusters
k_max <- 10

# calculate the total within sum of squares
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_scaled, k)$tot.withinss})

# visualize the results
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

As two categories seems to be sufficient to represent the data, the K-means clustering is applied again with two centers. From the figure below it is seen that the centers of the two groups are clearly separated for many of the variables. In the uppermost row red dots represents the group of low crime rate and black dots the group of high crime rate. As many of the variables are beyond my understanding, it is difficult for me to make conclusions of the results. However, for example, crime rate versus proportion of lower status population (lstat) is higher in the areas with high crime rate. Also the median value of owner occupied houses (medv) is lower in the high crime areas. Crime rate seems also in general higher when the distance from centers is low. On the other hand, the proportion of blacks in town does not seem to clearly influence the crime rate (although, this value is originally scaled as 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks, and therefore it is not so easy to understand what is going on here).

# k-means clustering
km <-kmeans(boston_scaled, centers = 2)

# plot the Boston dataset with clusters
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster, lower.panel = NULL)

Grouping with two centers (above) can be compared to grouping with three centers shown below. With three groups there are some overlapping with centers.

# k-means clustering
